iter::traits::double_ended::DoubleEndedI.doc:
This is the reverse version of [`Iterator::try_fold()`]: it takes
elements starting from the back of the iterator.

# Examples

Basic usage:

```
let a = ["1", "2", "3"];
let sum = a.iter()
    .map(|&s| s.parse::<i32>())
    .try_rfold(0, |acc, x| x.and_then(|y| Ok(acc + y)));
assert_eq!(sum, Ok(6));
```

Short-circuiting:

```
let a = ["1", "rust", "3"];
let mut it = a.iter();
let sum = it
    .by_ref()
    .map(|&s| s.parse::<i32>())
    .try_rfold(0, |acc, x| x.and_then(|y| Ok(acc + y)));
assert!(sum.is_err());

// Because it short-circuited, the remaining elements are still
// available through the iterator.
assert_eq!(it.next_back(), Some(&"1"));
```

ops::control_flow::ControlFlow::<B, C>::.doc:
Converts the `ControlFlow` into an `Option` which is `Some` if the
`ControlFlow` was `Break` and `None` otherwise.

# Examples

```
use std::ops::ControlFlow;

assert_eq!(ControlFlow::<&str, i32>::Break("Stop right there!").break_value(), Some("Stop right there!"));
assert_eq!(ControlFlow::<&str, i32>::Continue(3).break_value(), None);
```

